intro: Cuspidaria subincana, commonly known as the hairy cuspidaria, is a flowering plant belonging to the family Apiaceae. It is characterized by its slender, hairy stems and compound leaves with a serrated margin. The plant produces small, white to pale yellow flowers arranged in umbels, typical of the carrot family. It is native to regions of southern Europe and western Asia, often found in dry, rocky habitats. Due to its ornamental value and ecological role, it is occasionally cultivated in gardens.
